Principal Component Analysis (Case Study)

A PCA Case Study

  • This presentation is designed to serve as an example of how you might use PCA
  • The data come from a chemical analysis of wines grown in the same region of Italy
    • 13 characteristics are measured, though we suspect many of them are related
    • Further, it is known that 3 different cultivars provided these wine samples, so we are interested in seeing if the practices of these cultivars lead to noticeably different chemical profiles

Exploratory Data Analysis

  • Upon first seeing any dataset it is rare that you’ll immediately know the analysis strategy to use
  • Exploratory data analysis (EDA) is an important part of data science
  • The very first thing you should do is to use the summary function to get descriptive statistics on the variables you’ll be working with:

Exploratory Data Analysis

  • Because we’re interested in how variables are related, a scatterplot matrix is a useful next step in our EDA
  • R will construct this plot using the pairs function:
pairs(wine)

  • Notice how this graphic presents way too much information; however, we can clearly see that several variables appear related
  • The complexity of the scatterplot matrix leads us to consider PCA as a tool for understanding the multivariate nature of these data
    • Had this plot been easier to digest we might not want to use PCA

Principal Component Analysis

  • Recall that the prcomp function is used to perform PCA, and before using it we should standardize our data:
wine_std <- scale(wine)
P <- prcomp(wine_std)

  • The PCA output is intimidating to jump straight into, so let’s visualize the results instead

Principal Component Analysis

  • To begin, we’ll try to understand the first two principal components using a biplot, a type of plot that depicts the scores of data-points, and the loadings of the original variables, in any two of the principal component dimensions.

  • From the biplot, we first notice that PC1 explains quite a bit of variation in the original data (36.2%)
  • We also see that the biggest contributors to PC1 are flavanoids, phenols (proanthocyanins are a polyphenol), and alkalinity
  • Wines with a lot of flavanoid phenols have low scores in PC1, while wines with a lot of non-flavanoid phenols have high scores
  • PC2 explains a smaller but significant amount of variation, and its biggest contributors are ColorIntensity, Alcohol, Proline, Magnesium, and Ash

Choosing the Number of Components

  • In most PCA applications the first two principal components will almost always be of interest
    • How many principal components to consider beyond the first two is an important question
  • The most common way to make this decision is by looking at the proportion of variance explained
    • Like any variable, the scores in each principal component have variation
    • If the scores in a principal component dimension have a lot of variation, it implies that component is useful in separating the data (ie: there is a lot of unique information contained in that dimension)
    • If the scores do not have a lot of variation, it implies that component isn’t very interesting

Screeplots

  • A screeplot is a visual representation of the variance explained by each principal component

  • Here we see that 55% of the variation in the data exists in just two dimensions (PC1 and PC2)
  • 66% of the variation exists in three dimensions (PC1, PC2, and PC3)
  • These percentages might seem low, but they are actually quite good considering the original data had 13 dimensions!
  • Many methods have been proposed for selecting a suitable number of components (see: https://biologydirect.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/1745-6150-2-2) though there isn’t much consensus, so we’ll simply inspect the screeplot
  • Based upon the screeplot, it seems that using 2 or 3 principal components will provide an effective dimension reduction

Results

  • When introducing these data I mentioned the samples originated from 3 different cultivars in the same region
    • The first 2 principal components can clearly distinguish those cultivars
  • In contrast, no combination of the original variables provides such a clear two-dimensional representation

Next Steps

  • We’ll see later on that PCA has uses in clustering and supervised learning
  • For now, you should view PCA as a tool used to find and describe multivariate relationships in data containing more variables than you can comfortably display in a single graphic
